  "story": {
    "enabled": true,
    "heading": "The Story",
    "paragraphs": [
      "Geoff Barrow and Beth Gibbons met during a coffee break at an Enterprise Allowance course in Bristol in February 1991. With jazz guitarist Adrian Utley they became Portishead, named after Barrow's home town eight miles west of the city — and set about making music that moved at its own unhurried pace.",
      "Dummy (1994, Go! Beat) won the 1995 Mercury Music Prize ahead of shortlisted records by PJ Harvey, Oasis and Tricky, and spent 111 weeks on the UK albums chart. Built from scratchy samples, spy-soundtrack guitar and Gibbons' wounded voice, it became shorthand for the Bristol sound they shaped alongside Massive Attack and Tricky.",
      "Portishead (1997) darkened the palette, and Roseland NYC Live (1998) — cut with a full orchestra in New York — proved the songs could bleed on stage. Then came the long silence: eleven years between studio albums before Third (2008) swapped turntables for krautrock pulse and the air-raid panic of 'Machine Gun'. Every studio album they have released peaked at No. 2 in the UK.",
      "Since then Portishead surface only when it matters: an ABBA 'SOS' cover for Ben Wheatley's film High-Rise, a 2022 War Child benefit in Bristol — their first performance in seven years — and a 2025 recording of 'Roads' for Together For Palestine. Beth Gibbons released her debut solo album Lives Outgrown in 2024."
    ]
  },
